Spanish Stocks: Banesto, Gamesa, Iberdrola, Renovables, IAG Move

-- B y   J u l i e   C r u z   a n d   M a n u e l   B a i g o r r i
-- 
2011-03-09T17:12:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-08/iberdrola-iberdrola-renovables-iag-iberian-equity-preview.html
Spain’s IBEX 35 Index slid 9.2, or
0.1 percent, to 10,559.50 at the 5:30 p.m. close in  Madrid . The
 Madrid Stock Exchange General Index (MADX)  was little changed, adding
less than 0.1 percent.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
Spanish market. Symbols are in parentheses after company names.  Banco Espanol de Credito SA  (BTO SM) soared 8.5 percent to
6.59 euros, snapping six days of losses for the biggest gain
since May. The Spanish bank, known as Banesto, was raised to
“buy” from “neutral” at Goldman Sachs Group Inc.  Bankinter SA (BKT)   rose for a second day, gaining 2.3
percent to 4.66 euros, after it was raised to “accumulate”
from “hold” at  Caja Madrid .  Gamesa Corp Tecnologica SA (GAM)   surged 2.8 percent to
6.68 euros, the highest price in more than seven months. Spain’s
largest wind-turbine maker said it plans to start three new
plants in  India  by 2012.  Iberdrola Renovables SA (IBR SM) soared 11 percent to 3.04
euros, the largest increase since October 2008.  Iberdrola SA (IBE) 
 offered to buy out minority investors in its
alternative-energy unit for 2.5 billion euros ($3.5 billion) in
stock. Iberdrola shares fell 0.2 percent to 5.98 euros.  International Consolidated Airlines Group SA (IAG)  
jumped for a second day in three, adding 3.1 percent to 2.73
euros. The airline formed from the merger between British
Airways and Iberia will re-enter the IBEX 35 share index on
April 1, the Madrid-based IBEX committee said.  Natra SA (NAT)   sank for a third straight day, losing 5.2
percent to 2.12 euros. Bio Group  Brazil , a unit of Davene, has
decided not to exercise an option to buy the 47 percent stake
that Natra holds in  Natraceutical SA (NTC)  , according to a
regulatory filing. Natraceutical shares slumped 4.7 percent to
34.8 euro cents.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Julie Cruz in Frankfurt at 
